/b/54477031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_technology_sat-nav&ie=UTF8 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130128080401/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Sat-Nav-Technology/b/54477031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_technology_sat-nav&ie=UTF8 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-28 |title=Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 }}</ref>\n\n* Technology \u2013 audio and visual equipment (TVs, DVD players, Blu-ray Players, games consoles, phones, W.A.P./mobile phones,<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/oct/22/microsoft-mobilephones]{{Dead link|date=February 2011|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> iPods and more), DVDs and Blu-rays, communication devices (telephones, mobiles etc.), household electricals, white goods.  However Technology goods are now available only from the company's website after Marc Bolland's decision to close all in-store Technology departments in 2011.\n\n'''M&S Energy'''\nIn 2008 the company launched M&S Energy<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandsenergy.com/ |title=M&S Energy |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120905140416/http://www.mandsenergy.com/ |archivedate=5 September 2012 }}</ref> (in partnership with [[Scottish & Southern Energy]]) providing Electricity and Gas for the Home.  This was followed in February 2010 with Home Insulation.\n\n* '''Travelware'''- The [[Lexington light]] and [[Ontario heavy]] [[luggage]] and [[Scorpius utility]] [[rollercase]] lines.\n* '''Toy shop''' \u2013 Children's toys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Toys-Games-Kidswear/b/43656030?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_kids_toys-games&pf_rd_r=0GETYBBT9QQ0WRC9G1G1&pf_rd_m=A2BO0OYVBKIQJM&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_i=180882031&pf_rd_p=473397573&pf_rd_s=global-top-8 |title=Kids' Toys & Games : Kidswear : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Marks-and-Spencer-Play-Toaster/dp/B002F6ZPEI?ie=UTF8&qid=1257169909&categoryNodeID=53882031&page=&node=212420031&sr=1-7&mnSBrand=core&rh= |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120904093317/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Marks-and-Spencer-Play-Toaster/dp/B002F6ZPEI?ie=UTF8&qid=1257169909&categoryNodeID=53882031&page=&node=212420031&sr=1-7&mnSBrand=core&rh= |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-09-04 |title=Play Toaster \u2013 Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |accessdate=2009-11-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Meccano-Kids-Toys-Games-Kidswear/b/303579031 |title=Meccano : Kids' Toys & Games : Kidswear : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923145555/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Meccano-Kids-Toys-Games-Kidswear/b/303579031 |archive-date=23 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Age-0-3-My-1st-toys-Kids-Toys-Games-Kidswear/b/212419031 |title=Age 0\u20133 My 1st toys : Kids' Toys & Games : Kidswear : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930184714/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Age-0-3-My-1st-toys-Kids-Toys-Games-Kidswear/b/212419031 |archive-date=30 September 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Toys-Games-Kids/b/43656030?ie=UTF8&ie=UTF8 |title=Kids' Toys & Games : Kids' : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722110555/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Toys-Games-Kids/b/43656030?ie=UTF8&ie=UTF8 |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* '''First reader'''- Young [[children]]s' and [[toddler]]s' learning, story and fairy tale books.\n\n==Food and drink==\n\n===Own branded food stuffs===\n[[File:PercyPigs.jpeg|right|thumb|250px|A bag of Marks & Spencer's Percy [[Pigs]].]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Brand!! Line!! Products!!Source(s)\n|-\n| Count on us || \u2013 || Diet food in general|| \u2013\n|-\n|The cook range||-|| Multi-ethinic [[Take-out|Takeaway meals]]. ||-\n|-\n| The cook range || Cook Chinese || Ready-made [[Take-out|Chinese takeaway]]s. || \u2013\n|-\n| The cook range || Cook India|| Ready-made [[Take-out|Indian and takeaway]]s. || \u2013\n|-\n| The cook range || Cook East|| Ready-made [[Take-out|Thai takeaway]]s. || \u2013\n|-\n| Count on us|| Simply Fuller, Longer|| Specifically designed diet food to help you either lose or maintain weight. ||<ref>{{cite web|url=http://health.marksandspencer.com/our-health-ranges/simply-fuller-longer |title=Simply Fuller Longer : Our Healthy Ranges : M&S Health & Nutrition : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Health.marksandspencer.com |accessdate=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714042216/http://health.marksandspencer.com/our-health-ranges/simply-fuller-longer |archivedate=14 July 2011 }}</ref>\n|-\n| Simply Kids || \u2013 || Kids' [[biscuit]]s, sweets and [[cake]]s || \u2013\n|-\n| [[Gastropub (Marks & Spencer)|Gastropub]]  || \u2013 || [[TV dinner|ready meal]]s inspired by pub cuisine for home cooking ||<ref name=\"marksintime\">{{cite book | title = Marks in Time: 125 Years of Marks & Spencer | date = 3 September 2009 | last = Chislett | first = Helen | publisher = [[Weidenfeld and Nicolson]] | isbn = 978-0-297-85873-7 }}</ref><ref name=\"marksintime\"/>\n|-\n| Gastropub || Bistro range || [[Bistro]] inspired ready meals. ||-\n|-\n| Gastropub || Lunchtogo || [[Upmarket]] and businessmens' [[Party favor|grab bag]] and packed lunch meals. || .<ref name=\"Lunchtogo : Marks & Spencer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Lunchtogo/b/46596031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_food-wine_lunchtogo&pf_rd_r=0B02Z5SSS27Z62XAYXH5&pf_rd_m=A2BO0OYVBKIQJM&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_i=199645031&pf_rd_p=473397573&pf_rd_s=global-top-8 |title=Lunchtogo : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| Wise Buys || \u2013 || Discount and value food|| \u2013\n|-\n| Fair trade || \u2013 || [[Fair trade]] food, tea, coffee and wine || \u2013\n|-\n| Free range ||-|| [[free-range eggs]], [[Oakham chicken]] and field-bred pork. ||<ref name=\"marksintime\"/>\n|-\n| [[Percy pigs|Percy Pig and Penny Pig]]/[[Colin the Caterpillar]]  || \u2013 || Percy Pig and Penny Pig/Colin Caterpillar sweets ||<ref name=\"marksintime\"/><ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n|}\n\n===Major brands===\n'''Free range'''\n* Free range \u2013- [[free-range eggs]], [[Oakham chicken]] and field-bred pork. [[Oakham chicken]] is exclusive to M&S, and is not from the [[Rutland]] town of [[Oakham]]. Free-range eggs have been on sale since 1997 and M&S is deeply committed to upholding animal welfare.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/>\n\n'''Gastropub'''\n\n* [[Gastropub (Marks & Spencer)|Gastropub]] are ''[[TV dinner|ready meal]]s inspired by pub cuisine for home cooking''<ref name=\"marksintime\"/>  It got a 'Golden pub-meal commendation' in 2005.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/>\n* Lunchtogo \u2013 [[upmarket]] and businessmen's [[Party favor|grab bag]] and packed lunch meals.<ref name=\"Lunchtogo : Marks & Spencer\"/> The 'Food to go line' was merged into it during the festive season of 2010\u20132011.\n* Bistro range- A range of Bistro inspired meals launched during the festive season of 2010\u20132011.\n\n'''Percy Pig'''\n{{main article|Percy Pig}}\n'''Percy Pigs''' is a popular brand of pig-shaped raspberry-flavoured [[confectionery]] made under licence in Germany for Marks & Spencer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britstore.co.uk/p21/Marks-and-Spencer-Percy-Pig-sweets-170g-bag-/product_info.html |title=Marks and Spencer Percy Pig sweets 170g bag Britstore |publisher=Britstore.co.uk |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718103815/http://www.britstore.co.uk/p21/Marks-and-Spencer-Percy-Pig-sweets-170g-bag-/product_info.html |archive-date=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neenaw.co.uk/index.php/ambulances/374/the-percy-pig-incident/ |title=Nee Naw \u2013 The Percy Pig Incident |publisher=Neenaw.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-04-28}}</ref> The sweets first appeared in stores in the mid-1990s. The name \"Percy Pig\" has now been trademarked by Marks & Spencer.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> More than \u00a310,000,000 was grossed between June 2009 and 2010 in Percy Pig sales in Marks & Spencer's UK branches alone.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> They are made up of just under 3.5% fruit juice.<ref>[http://www.Stinerland.co.de/blog/percy-pigs-contains-actual-pig/] {{dead link|date=July 2017}}</ref>\n\nPercy Pigs were created in 1995 and were sold in [[strawberry]] and [[raspberry]] flavours.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/> Until 2008, Percy Pigs were available in 100, 200 and 400&nbsp;grams. The packaging has not changed size, but the middle size now contains 170&nbsp;grams and the large size now contains 340&nbsp;grams. There is also the related ''[[Colin the Caterpillar]]'' sweet that was first launched in the festive season of 2008\u20132009.\n\n===Alcohol===\n\nM&S has an extensive wine and beer range,<ref name=\"marksandspencer11\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Wine-Food-Wine/b/44092030?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_food-wine_wine |title=Wine : Food & Wine : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091219112225/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Wine-Food-Wine/b/44092030?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_food-wine_wine |archive-date=19 December 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which was first started in 1973.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/>\n\nIn 2006 and 2007, M&S entered over a hundred of its own wines into two wine competitions, ''[[Decanter (magazine)|The Decanter World Wine Awards]]'' and The [[International Wine Challenge]]. Both years, almost every wine won an award, ranging from the 2005 Secano Pinot Noir, Leyda Valley, Chile (Best Pinot Noir in the world for under \u00a310) to the Rosada Cava (Commended).<ref name=\"Decanter World Wine Awards 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.decanter.com/worldwineawards/2007/dwwa_search.php?rsearch=M%26S |title=Decanter World Wine Awards 2007 |publisher=Decanter.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref>\n\n* Alcohol ''M&S has an extensive wine and beer range,<ref name=\"marksandspencer11\"/> which was first started in 1973.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> In 2006 and 2007, M&S entered over a hundred of its own wines into two wine competitions, ''[[Decanter (magazine)|The Decanter World Wine Awards]]'' and The [[International Wine Challenge]]. Both years, almost every wine won an award, ranging from the 2005 Secano Pinot Noir, Leyda Valley, Chile (Best Pinot Noir in the world for under \u00a310) to the Rosada Cava (Commended).<ref name=\"Decanter World Wine Awards 2007\"/>''\n* Beer \u2013 UK and EU-sourced beers.\n* Wine \u2013 a worldwide selection of fine wine, including [[Chardonnay]] and [[Syrah|Shiraz]]\n\n===Branded food products===\n\n* In November 2009, Marks & Spencer announced that it would begin selling up to 400 branded lines, such as [[Kellogg's]] & [[H. J. Heinz Company|Heinz]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/nov/04/marks-and-spencer-profits-higher | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Julia | last=Kollewe | title=Marks and Spencer profits edge up but says consumer confidence still fragile | date=2009-11-04}}</ref> In November 2010 it was speculated that they may discontinue up to 300 of these branded products to push their brand further.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2010/nov/09/marks-and-spencer-foreign-expansion | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Graeme | last=Wearden | title=Marks & Spencer to revamp stores and push own brand | date=2010-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==Gift shop/Christmas gifts and ideas shop==\n\nThe gift shop sells [[cut flower]]s, greetings cards, Christmas [[hamper]]s, jewellery, watches and [[upmarket]] chocolates.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Flowers-Gifts/b/199645031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_flowers-gifts&pf_rd_r=13JGMTVZBHZ0ATFQKHMJ&pf_rd_m=A2BO0OYVBKIQJM&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_i=44001030&pf_rd_p=473397573&pf_rd_s=global-top-8 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130129030440/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Flowers-Gifts/b/199645031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_flowers-gifts&pf_rd_r=13JGMTVZBHZ0ATFQKHMJ&pf_rd_m=A2BO0OYVBKIQJM&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_i=44001030&pf_rd_p=473397573&pf_rd_s=global-top-8 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2013-01-29 |title=Flowers & Gifts : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2009-11-07 }}</ref> The 'Christmas gifts and ideas shop' is the Christmas version and sells gifts, toys and Christmas decorations. The online flower service was accused of unfair trading and using [[Google]] to [[piggy-back advertise]] on online searches aimed at [[Interflora]] online in 2010.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-11531677 | work=BBC News | title=Interflora sues Marks & Spencer over Google ad links | date=2010-10-13}}</ref>\n\n==M&S BANK==\n\nFormerly M&S Money, M&S has offered financial services including ISAs, loans, credit cards, car insurance and holiday insurance through its financial services department<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.marksandspencer.com/ |title=M&S Money \u2013 Credit Cards, Insurance, Savings and Loans |publisher=Money.marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref> since the 1980s. Since mid-2012 M&S has also offered two monthly paid for current account options. The current accounts offer a contactless Visa debit card designed by Conran, rewards and benefits including travel insurance, hot drinks vouchers and access to a high interest savings account.\n\n==M&S Energy==\n\nM&S was scheduled to launch its energy service in 2016.\n\n==M&S TV and online services==\nProducts could be ordered online since the mid-2000s, in response to some like [[Tesco]] launching their pioneering [[Tesco.com]] home shopping delivery service in the early 2000s. Tesco, M&S and others are expanding rapidly into this new niche market.\n\n[[M&S TV]] is an online TV station to advertise goods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/MS-TV/b/311612031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_ms-tv&ie=UTF8 |title=M&S TV : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513060309/http://www.marksandspencer.com/MS-TV/b/311612031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_ms-tv&ie=UTF8 |archive-date=13 May 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe online flower service was accused of unfair trading and using [[Google]] to [[piggy-back advertise]] on online searches aimed at [[Interflora]] online in 2010.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/>\n\nThe [[John Lewis (department store)|John Lewis]] shopping chain beat M&S to the title of the UK's best high-street website by late 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bold |first=Ben |url=http://www.marketingmagazine.co.uk/channel/DigitalMedia/article/1035596/John-Lewis-beats-M-S-UKs-best-high-street-website/ |title=John Lewis beats M&S as UK's best high-street website \u2013 Marketing news |publisher=Marketing magazine |date=2010-10-19 |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Former clothing ranges and product types==\n\n===Old labels===\n'St Margaret', 'St Michael' and 'Homecare' brands were the time-honoured brand labels that fell out of use in the company wide re-branding campaign of the early 2000s.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> The stylish 1996\u20131997 'Orient Express Tagged' brand was the first of numerous new brands, most of which were in women's and children's clothes.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> The 'Orient Express Tagged' brand<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> was revived in 2007 as the year long 'Orient Express Platform 10' brand<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> and was part of the inspiration behind the 'Portfolio' brand.<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> The men's Autograph brand was then launched in 2000<ref name=\"marksintime\"/> and continues to this day.<ref name=\"marksandspencer6\"/><ref name=\"marksandspencer7\"/><ref name=\"marksandspencer8\"/><ref name=\"corporate.marksandspencer.com\"/>\n\n'Plus range maternity \u2013 larger sizes of maternity clothes were absorbed into the already existing 'Limited Collection Maternity', under the name of 'M&S Maternity'<ref name=\"marksandspencer2\"/> in 2008 to simplify administration.<ref name=\"marksandspencer1\"/>\n\nThe women's 'Perfect' and 'Essential' sub-brands were largely relaunched in 2009 as the 'Portfolio' range, but with out the [[Upmarket|high end]] designer blouses. Perfect still operates in men's rain coats and cookware. Perfect was relaunced in January 2010 as a [[seasonal]] sub-brand of Portfolio.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n[[Sir Stuart Rose]] axed both the ailing casual [[Fashion|menswear]] brand [[SP Clothing]], the [[View From]] [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]] range, the [[David Beckham]] children's range, [[DB07]] clothes, the teenage range [[Per Una Due]] and several food lines in 2004, because he thought the business' stock inventory management had become 'too complicated',.<ref name=\"thisismoney.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Timberland CEO Jeffrey Swartz |url=http://www.just-style.com/analysis/sir-stuart-hands-over-golden-baton_id108297.aspx |title=Sir Stuart hands over golden baton |publisher=Just-style.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref>\n\nThe retailer had launched several brands, sub-brands and line of [[womenswear]] and [[Childrenswear]] in recent years such as Indigo Collection Junior, Indigo Collection and Portfolio. Indigo Collection aimed at women over 30s, while Portfolio 45s. Overall, M &S has ten womenswear sub-brands and sub-sub-brands, such as Per Una and Autograph, but only six menswear brands, such as [[Blue Harbour]], [[North Coast (brand)|North Coast]] and Collezione by 2010.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n===The 2008-9 restructuring plan===\n\nAs part of the 2008-9 restructuring plan, nine sub-brands deemed to be unprofitable, unnecessary or superfluous were either discontinued, merged or relaunched in 2008, with further activity, including some store closures, occurring in both 2009 and 2010.\n\n* 'Conde Nast' (the M&S clothes, not [[Cond\u00e9 Nast Publications]]) designer clothes were a planned sub-brand that was not launched over the festive season of 2009\u20132010 because of the [[credit crunch]] and became part of the 'Indigo Collection' and 'Portfolio' lines.\n* All the Kid's furniture (the 'Kid's bedroom' line), bedding and electronic toys (part of the 'Toy shop' brand) were re-grouped and expanded as the 'Kids at home' brand in January 2010,<ref>{{cite web|author=StyleJunkee: Fashion. Beauty. Homes. |url=http://style.sonorika.co.uk/news/a--kids-at-homea--launches-at-marks-and-spencer/478702 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714084947/http://style.sonorika.co.uk/news/a--kids-at-homea--launches-at-marks-and-spencer/478702 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2012-07-14 |title=\u2018Kids at Home\u2019 launches at Marks and Spencer &#124; Sonorika.com |publisher=Style.sonorika.co.uk |date=2010-01-20 |accessdate=2011-07-18 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-At-Home-E-Catalogues-Whats-New/b/77098031 |title=Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608221223/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-At-Home-E-Catalogues-Whats-New/b/77098031 |archive-date=8 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Bedroom-Kids/b/198106031?ie=UTF8&ie=UTF8 |title=Kids' Bedroom : Kids' : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722110543/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Bedroom-Kids/b/198106031?ie=UTF8&ie=UTF8 |archive-date=22 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> but the merger had been repealed and broken back up by July 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Bedroom-Kids/b/198106031?ie=UTF8&intid=gnav_kids_kids-bedroom&pf_rd_r=0T597QP8W6JJJGX8HAV8&pf_rd_m=A2BO0OYVBKIQJM&pf_rd_t=101&pf_rd_i=43126030&pf_rd_p=473397573&pf_rd_s=global-top-8 |title=Kids' Bedroom : Kids' : Marks & Spencer |publisher=Marksandspencer.com |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913214641/http://www.marksandspencer.com/Kids-Bedroom-Kids/b/198106031?ie=UTF8 |archive-date=13 September 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Perfection (Autograph's & Per Una's perfumeries merged into one in early 2009)\n\nM&S also began to sell other branded goods like [[Kellogg's Corn Flakes]] from November 2008.<ref>{{cite web|author=Graham Hiscott |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/city-news/2009/11/04/marks-and-spencer-to-start-selling-top-brands-115875-21796883/ |title=Marks and Spencer to start selling top brands |website=Mirror.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref> and may ditch its own branded food<ref name=\"ausfoodnews.com.au\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausfoodnews.com.au/2010/10/19/marks-and-spencer-may-cut-sales-of-name-brands.html |title=Marks and Spencer may cut sales of name brands &#124; Australian Food News |website=Ausfoodnews.com.au |date=2010-10-19 |accessdate=2017-07-07}}</ref> in 2011 due to poor turn over beyond the 'Food to go', 'Lunchtogo' and 'Gastropub' lines.\n\n===The 2010 product audit===\nAnother review and re-branding exercise was planned for late 2010 and 2011 after several years of declining sales in the womenswear department as born out by an [[audit]] conducted by the firm the [[Retail Knowledge Bank]] in the August 2010.\n\n'PU Active' was a brief foray by Per Una into the casual [[sportswear (activewear)|sportswear]] lines in the September 2010, but it was scrapped during its infancy by the October due to poor sales figures.\n\n===The '2011 brand cull'===\n[[Marc Bolland]] had considered axing several brands in early 2011 after an [[audit]] by the [[Retail Knowledge Bank]] in the August 2010, revealed that sales of M&S womenswear were at a ten-year low. The audit covered both the [[Limited Collection]], [[Autograph]], [[Autograph Weekend]], [[Classic Collection]], [[Per Una]], [[Portfolio (brand)|Portfolio]] and [[Indigo]].<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"thisismoney.co.uk 512068\">{{cite web|author=Neil Craven |url=http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/news/article.html?in_article_id=512068&in_page_id=2 |title=M&S clothing brands set for overhaul |publisher=This is Money |date=2010-08-15 |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2010, [[Draper magazine]] claimed that Per Una was the only clothing brand that was not at risk of being axed in Mr Bolland's shake-up of the plethora of clothing brands sold at M&S.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> [[Per Una]] was planned to stay due to its successful and distinctive flair, but [[Portfolio (brand)|Portfolio]] and [[Indigo]] were planned go due to poor sales.<ref name=\"dailymail.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"thisismoney.co.uk 512068\"/> The [[Limited Collection]], [[Autograph]], [[Autograph Weekend]], [[Classic Collection]] brands were being considered for the cull during mid-2010, but were later given a reprieve.<ref>{{cite web|author=Julian Dunkerton, chief executive, SuperGroup |url=http://www.just-style.com/news/bolland-review-to-streamline-ms-clothing-brands_id108648.aspx |title=Bolland review to streamline M&S clothing brands? |publisher=Just-style.com |date=2010-08-17 |accessdate=2011-07-18}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed in the November 2010, that there would be a major 3 year [[UK|UK]] store revamp, which would cost between  \u00a3850,000,000 and \u00a3900,000,000 and a cull of what Mr Bolland called \"the often confusing\" store layouts and \"indistinguishable brands\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20101109-705850.html |work=The Wall Street Journal |title=2nd UPDATE: Marks & Spencer Gets UK Makeover |date=2010-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112012607/http://online.wsj.com/article/BT-CO-20101109-705850.html |archivedate=12 November 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE6A70V420101109 | work=Reuters | first=Mark | last=Potter | title=UPDATE 5-Marks & Spencer's new CEO lifts investment | date=2010-11-09}}</ref>\n\nM&S also announced it was planning to take over [[Twiggy]]'s [[Twiggy international]] label some during the winter 2010\u20132011.<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/>\n\n===The May\u2013August 2011 Corporate revamp===\n\nFashion guru Sara Bradley was reported in March as planning to take a 'senior role' within M&S's clothing business by mid-2011.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Neil Craven |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/money/article-1363306/Asda-rocked-M-S-snatches-new-fashion-guru.html#ixzz1HEAAUb00 |title=Asda is rocked as M&S snatches its new fashion guru |work=The Daily Mail |location=UK |date=5 March 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe firm's packaging, clothing brands and labels will change. The retailer has announced plans to abandon the \"Marks & Spencer\" label from its clothes, replacing it with \"[[M&S Woman]]\" and \"[[M&S Man]]\". It will also re-launch its [[Per Una]] and North Coast clothing sub-brands.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ph.paylesser.com/blog/10-unique-gift-ideas-bride-groom/|title=10 unique gift ideas for the Bride and Groom|date=21 September 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe official goal was to be better at food than supermarkets and better at clothes and general merchandise than department stores.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reece |first=Damian |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/comment/damianreece/8534681/Marks-and-Spencer-needs-to-show-its-future-is-in-retail.html |title=Marks & Spencer needs to show its future is in retail |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-05-25 |accessdate=2011-07-18 |location=London}}</ref>\n\nAlison Jones, who is the daughter of [[Sir David Jones]], joined M&S on 2 June, as the new [[brand director for general merchandise]], under the leadership of [[marketing director]] Steve Sharp. She had gained previous experience at [[Topshop]] and [[Debenhams]].  The role has been created to give a more cohesive approach to M&S's branding and help develop and co-ordinate the brand and strategy for M&S's clothing division.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/8551000/Marks-and-Spencer-poaches-Arcadia-marketing-director.html |title=Marks & Spencer poaches Arcadia marketing director |publisher=Telegraph |date=2011-06-02 |accessdate=2011-07-18 |location=London |first=James |last=Hall}}</ref>\n\n===May 2013 revamp===\n15 May 2013 saw the launch of the 'Best of British' range as well as the overhaul of Per Una and Indigo.\n<ref name=\"mirror2\"/> Patrick Bousquet-Chavanne \u2013 currently M&S's corporate director of strategy implementation and business development became the new marketing director and will succeed Steven Sharp in July. Mark Bolland also vowed to bring back \"quality and style\"<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"Emma Simpson\"/><ref name=\"BBC News\"/>\n\n==The new 2017 seasonal collections==\nThe 'Best of British' range had been discontinued by 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704233528/http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women |archive-date=4 July 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704233528/http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women |date=4 July 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women |title=Archived copy |access-date=5 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170704233528/http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women |archive-date=4 July 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSeveral new lines had started. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/women|title=Womenswear \u2013 Clothing, Shoes & Accessories For Women \u2013 M&S|website=Marksandspencer.com}}</ref>\n#Autumn 17 Preview (adverts for the Altum collection)\n#Flattering Sleeves (female)\n#The Holiday Shop (both genders)\n#Occasionwear (both genders)\n#Online Exclusives (online only\\both genders)\n#Wedding Outfit Inspiration (female) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/l/women/wedding-outfit-inspiration|title=Wedding Outfit Inspiration \u2013 Women \u2013 M&S|website=Marksandspencer.com}}</ref>\n#The White Collection (white clothes for both genders)\n#Wedding Shop (both genders) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/c/wedding-shop|title=Wedding Shop \u2013 Wedding Fashion, Clothes & Accessories \u2013 M&S|website=Marksandspencer.com}}</ref>\n#Altum collection (both genders)\n\n===The new 2017 seasonal collections===\n'The White Collection' was discontinued by mid 2018.\n\nA new line was started.\n#M&S Collection ('elevated' female everyday essentials) <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marksandspencer.com/l/women/mands-collection#CtYgBcJ4oWZ2BgcG.99|title=M&S Collection Womens Clothing \u2013 Classic Workwear \u2013 M&S|website=Marksandspencer.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Waitrose]]\n* [[Supermarket]]\n* [[Million Model Catwalk]]\n* [[Fashion Targets Breast Cancer]]\n* [[Foo Go]]\n* [[Bistro]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of Marks and Spencer brands}}\n[[Category:Marks & Spencer]]\n[[Category:British brands]]\n[[Category:Lists of brands by company|Marks and Spencer]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Script-assisted fixes: perCS1andMOS:ITALICS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Marks_%26_Spencer_brands"}
{"title_page": "Rajasthan Youth Congress", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox political youth organization\n | colorcode           = DeepSkyBlue\n | name                = Rajasthan Youth Congress\n | native_name         = \u0930\u093e\u091c\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928 \u092f\u0941\u0935\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\n |abbreviation         = RPYC\n | colorcode           = DeepSkyBlue\n | logo                = [[File:Indian Youth Congress Logo.jpg]]\n | State President     = [[Mukesh Bhakar]] \n | national in charge  = [[Krishna Allavaru]]\n | national president  = [[Srinivas B V]]\n | State in charge     = [[Abraham Roy Mani]] [[Dr. Palak Verma]] [[Manju Tongad]]\n | Vice president      = [[Amardeen Fakir]]|[[Rakesh Meena]]|[[Sanjta Sihag]]\n | mother party        = [[Indian Youth Congress]] \n | ideology            = [[Populism]]| [[Social liberalism]]|[[Democratic socialism]]|[[Social democracy]]|[[Secularism]]|[[Big tent]]\n | website             = [http://iyc.in/ iyc.in] \n | headquarters       = B.613 SAWAI JAISINGH HIGHWAY BANIPARK JAIPUR, Rajasthan\n | founded             = 1960 \n}}\n\nThe '''Rajasthan Youth Congress''' or RPYC is the state wing of the [[Indian Youth Congress]], youth wing of [[Indian National Congress]].\n'''[[Mukesh Bhakar]]''' is the President of Rajasthan Pradesh Youth Congress. [[Mukesh Bhakar]] is also MLA from [[Ladnun]] assembly in [[Nagaur District]]. <ref> https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n'''Amardeen Fakir''' is the  Executive Vice President of Rajasthan Youth Congress, '''Rakesh Meena''' and '''Sanjita Sihag'''is the State Vice prasident of Rajasthan Youth Congress. \nAlso there are 10 general secretaries and 40+ secretaries having charge of 39 district units of the organization.\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://rajasthanpcc.com// Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee, Official website]\n* [http://inc.in Indian National Congress, Official website]\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Indian political parties}}\n{{India topics}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.iyc.in iyc.in]\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n\n[[Category:Indian Youth Congress|*]]\n[[Category:Politics of Madhya Pradesh]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox political youth organisation\n| name= Madhya Rajasthan Youth Congress \n| native_name= \u0930\u093e\u091c\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928 \u092f\u0941\u0935\u093e \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938\n|abbreviation      = RPYC\n| colorcode = DeepSkyBlue\n| logo = [[File:Indian Youth Congress Logo.jpg]]\n| State President = [[Mukesh Bhakar]] \n| national in charge  = [[Krishna Allavaru]]\n| national president  = [[Srinivas B V]]\n| State in charge = [[Abraham Roy Mani]] [[Dr. Palak Verma]] [[Manju Tongad]]\n| executive vice president = [[Amardeen Fakir]]\n| associate vice president = [[Rakesh Meena]] [[Sanjta Sihag]]\n| mother party = [[Indian Youth Congress]] \n| ideology = [[Populism]]| [[Social liberalism]]|[[Democratic socialism]]|[[Social democracy]]|[[Secularism]]|[[Big tent]]\n|website             = [http://iyc.in/ iyc.in] \n|  headquarters      = B.613 SAWAI JAISINGH HIGHWAY BANIPARK JAIPUR, Rajasthan\n| founded             = 1960 \n}}\n\nThe '''Rajasthan Youth Congress''' or RPYC is the state wing of the [[Indian Youth Congress]], youth wing of [[Indian National Congress]].\n'''[[Mukesh Bhakar]]''' is the President of Rajasthan Pradesh Youth Congress. [[Mukesh Bhakar]] is also MLA from [[Ladnun]] assembly in [[Nagaur District]]. <ref> https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-